## AUDIENCE INTELLIGENCE

**Blog Gen instruction:** This section is your primary creative brief. Use this audience data to inform every paragraph, every sentence, every word choice. You are writing for this specific person with this specific intent. Satisfy them completely.

### Intent-Specific Audience Profile

**Who they are:** Women 18–35 with fair/pale/porcelain skin, predominantly but not exclusively cool-toned, mix of DIY home manicure and regular salon clients. Active TikTok and Pinterest users. Many self-identify as "very pale" or "I burn easily." Some are fair with warm undertones and feel overlooked by generic nail content. Some are redheads or blondes. Many have had the experience of picking a shade that looked wrong without understanding why.

**What they want from this post:** They want to see what looks genuinely beautiful on skin like theirs. They're not here to learn colour theory — they want to finish the post feeling excited about specific shades and confident they won't waste money on another polish that makes their hands look washed out or their nails disappear.

**What satisfies them:** Specific shade direction tied to their undertone. Honest guidance on shades that seem risky (dark colours, nudes) but can work when chosen correctly. Visuals that show what each shade looks like on actual pale skin — not a swatch on a colour ring. An explanation of why shades go wrong, not just which ones do.

**What frustrates them:** Generic lists that assume all fair skin is cool-toned. Guides that just say "avoid dark colours" without explaining why or when dark can actually work. Nudes that disappear into their skin. The experience of a shade looking perfect in the bottle and wrong on their hands. Posts that feel written for medium skin with "fair skin" tagged onto them.

### Top 5 Pain Points

1. Picking a nude or pastel that looks beautiful in the bottle and makes their hands look like they have no nails at all — the "invisible hand" problem
2. Not knowing whether they have cool or warm undertones, so they apply the wrong shade families and then blame the colour
3. Choosing a red that looks amazing in the bottle but reads orange or purple on their hand
4. Wanting to wear dark shades (burgundy, navy, deep plum) but being told to avoid dark colours — and not knowing if they can actually pull it off
5. Feeling that fair-skin nail guides are written for cool-toned fair skin only, leaving warm-toned fair women without usable guidance

